TI  - Conversion of crude glycerol to biohydrogen by locally isolated Klebsiella pneumoniae via dark fermentation
PY  - 2025
T2  - Clean Technologies and Environmental Policy
VL  - 27
IS  - 1
C7  - 121379
SP  - 235
EP  - 250
DO  - 10.1007/s10098-024-02891-2
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85193702588&doi=10.1007%2Fs10098-024-02891-2&partnerID=40&md5=6e2604026302fd95e2be19ff34e9588f
AB  - Bioconversion of crude glycerol (CG) to biohydrogen (Bio-H2) is promising due to being a cost-effective and environmentally friendly avenue for waste reduction and clean energy. However, the limited availability of microbes capable in anaerobic CG metabolism has hindered Bio-H2 production, resulting in its low yield through bacterial conversion. Hence, this study sought to isolate and identify indigenous bacteria, focusing on their potential to efficiently consume and convert CG into Bio-H2. Utilising the 16S rRNA sequencing technique and the BLAST gene bank database, 10 isolated colonies, which were all identified as Klebsiella species, exhibited notable Bio-H2 production based on the evolved gas globules (EGGs) observed during dark fermentation. Based on the hydrogen yield analysis, Klebsiella pneumoniae strain HS11286 (CG1) generated the highest volume of Bio-H2 with a reading of 72.5 mL. The research then focused on the kinetic study for growth and substrate utilisation by the kinetic Monod model and the modified Gompertz equation. In the metabolism of CG by K. pneumoniae, 6 h was required for lag phase to adapt to start proliferating, generating Bio-H2 and metabolites. Based on the HPLC results, three metabolites were produced during the metabolism of CG (i.e., 1,3-propanediol, propionic acid, and ethanol). The kinetic analysis revealed a growth (µ) of 0.106 h−1, glycerol consumption rate (Qgly) of 1.572 g/L/h, and the yield coefficients Yp/x, Yp/s, and Yx/s of 30,758.51 mL/g cell, 479.26 mL/g substrate, and 0.016 g cell/g substrate, respectively. The modified Gompertz model predicted Bio-H2 production of 10,155 mL at 620 mL/h with a 6 h lag period. In summary, K. pneumoniae strain HS11286 demonstrated the capacity to produce almost 10 L of hydrogen within 48 h without substrate pre-treatment, bacteria acclimatisation or genetic engineering. This not only brought forth a new indigenous bacteria as a potential hydrogen producer; it also underscored the strain’s latent capability to produce a higher yield of Bio-H2 in a short amount of time by forgoing pre-treatment or acclimation, distinguishing it from other microbes. © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer-Verlag GmbH Germany, part of Springer Nature 2024.
